the <ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">Chinese</ENAMEX> invaded, though he did urge him to leave <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Lhasa</ENAMEX>.

            As for
the invasion, the film understandably simplifies events--it leaves out, for
instance, the unheeded pleas for help made by <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Tibet</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">India</ENAMEX> that preceded the
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">invasion</ENAMEX> and the unheeded pleas to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">United Nations</ENAMEX> that followed it--but on
the whole, the movie is fairly accurate. <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Tibet</ENAMEX> did fall to the <ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">Chinese</ENAMEX> in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">11</TIMEX>
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">days</TIMEX>, and an incident shown in the film as crucial to the success of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">invasion</ENAMEX> was indeed definitive--when, in a startling act of cowardice, Ngabo
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Ngawang Jigme</ENAMEX> (played in the movie by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">B.D. Wong</ENAMEX>), a <ENAMEX TYPE="NATIONALITY">Tibetan</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">minister</ENAMEX> in charge
